[[Image:Main Street, Flagstaff, ME.jpg|thumb|right|Main Street c. 1915]] '''Flagstaff''' is a [[ghost town]] and former [[New England town|town]] in [[Somerset County, Maine|Somerset County]], [[Maine]], [[United States]], near the existing town of [[Eustis, Maine|Eustis]] and about 20 miles north of [[Rangeley, Maine|Rangeley]].
[[Benedict Arnold]] camped here on his Quebec expedition and erected a flagstaff, hence the name.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9V1IAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA126#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=126}}</ref>
The town was abandoned and dismantled (and legally disincorporated) in 1950 to allow construction of a hydroelectric dam on the [[Dead River (Kennebec River)|Dead River]], which enlarged [[Flagstaff Lake (Maine)|Flagstaff Lake]] and submerged the site of the settlement.
The song "Below" by [[Slaid Cleaves]] on his 2004 album ''Wishbones'' refers to the destruction of the town, although it is not mentioned by name. The lyrics specifically mention the Dead River, and its general location.
