===Random House===
In 1983, the U.S. publishing company [[Random House]] was granted paperback rights to books in the Care Bears franchise through American Greetings and General Mills, as Parker Brothers was unable to secure the exclusive publishing rights at the time.<ref>{{cite journal| title = Business Week| url = https://books.google.com/?id=j58pAQAAIAAJ| accessdate = September 21, 2010| volume = Part 1| year = 1983| publisher = [[McGraw Hill]]| page = 98| quote = For example, because Parker has no track record in books, it was unable to obtain exclusive publishing rights to the Care Bears. American Greetings and General Mills cautiously dealt the paperback rights to Random House Inc....| work = [[BusinessWeek]] }}</ref>  Bruce Jones, a Parker Brothers staffer, could not secure the exclusive publishing rights, and had to settle for a split license with Random House.<ref name=rules/>{{rp|220}}  During the mid-1980s, [[Sandoz|Dorsey Laboratories]] promoted its [[Novartis|Triaminic]] cough medicine through a Random House publication, ''The Care Bears Help Chase Colds'';<ref>{{cite book| last1 = Murphy| first1 = Catherine Frey| last2 = Hambleton| first2 = Vicki| last3 = Broerman| first3 = Joan| last4 = Pfitsch| first4 = Patricia| title = Children's Writer Guide to 2000| url = https://books.google.com/?id=9g8ZjO5uKQ0C| accessdate = August 13, 2010| year = 2000| publisher = The Writer's Bookstore| isbn = 1-889715-03-4| page = 163| quote = Dorsey Laboratories, in cooperation with Random House, developed a children's book, ''The Care Bears Help Chase Colds'', to promote the sale of their Triaminic cold-care products. }}</ref> this promotion helped sell over two million units of the product, along with a free copy of said book.<ref>{{cite book| last = Kremer| first = John| title = 101 Ways to Market Your Books For Publishers and Authors| url = https://books.google.com/?id=KpvgAAAAMAAJ| accessdate = August 13, 2010| year = 1986| publisher = Ad-Lib Publications| isbn = 0-912411-08-2| page = 235 }}</ref>

